<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_trig_computing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Computing with trigonometric functions</title>
<objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Derive the side lengths of
          45-45-90 and 30-60-90 triangles.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use reference triangles to calculate certain values of sine and cosine exactly.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Think critically about the difference between radian and degree measures of angles,
          and the resulting values of sine and cosine.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          See how the alternate definition of sine and cosine via right triangles results in the same values for acute angles.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Define the remaining trigonometric functions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
</objectives>
<subsection>
    <title>Side lengths of two special right triangles</title>
    <p>
      Our in-depth study of the unit circle is motivated by our desire to better understand the behavior of circular functions.
      Recall that as we traverse a circle,
      the height of the point moving along the circle generates a function that depends on distance traveled along the circle.
      Wherever possible,
      we'd like to be able to identify the exact height of a given point on the unit circle.
      Two special right triangles enable us to determine precisely an important collection of points on the unit circle.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="th_special_triangles">
      <title>Special right triangles</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
           
            <li>
                 <title>45-45-90 triangle</title> 
                <p>
                    Let <m>T</m> be a triangle with angles 45,45, and 90 degrees. If the hypotenuse of <m>T</m> has length <m>1</m>, then the two remaining sides of <m>T</m> have length <m>\sqrt{2}/2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>30-60-90 triangle</title>
                <p>
                    Let <m>T</m> be a triangle with angles 30,60, and 90 degrees. If the hypotenuse of <m>T</m> has length <m>1</m>, then the side of <m>T</m> opposite the 30-degree angle has length <m>1/2</m>, and the side of <m>T</m> opposite the 60-degree angle has length <m>\sqrt{3}/2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <figure xml:id="fig_special_triangles">
        <caption>Special right triangles</caption>
        <sidebyside valigns="bottom bottom" widths="30% 50%">
            <figure xml:id="fig_45_45_90">
                <caption>45-45-90 triangle</caption>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription>45-45-90 triangle</shortdescription>
                    <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi/4
beta=pi/4
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
T=polygon([(0,0),(a,0),(a,b),(0,0)], color='blue', fill=False,axes=False)
t1=text("$1$",(a/2,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$",(a+.05,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$",(a/2,0-.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
s1=parametric_plot(.05*c(t), (t,0,alpha), color='red')
s2=parametric_plot(hyp+.05*c(t), (t,-pi/2-beta, -pi/2), color='red')
s3=line([(a-.05,0),(a-.05,.05),(a,.05)],color="red")
a1=text("$45^\circ$",.1*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
a2=text("$45^\circ$",hyp+.1*c(-pi/2-beta/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
# a3=text("$90^\circ$",leg+.1*c(3*pi/4),color="black",fontsize=16)
T+t1+t2+t3+s1+s2+s3+a1+a2
                    </sageplot>

                </image>
            </figure>
<figure xml:id="fig_30-60-90">
                <caption>30-60-90 triangle</caption>
                <image>
                    <shortdescription>45-45-90 triangle</shortdescription>
                    <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi/6
beta=pi/3
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
T=polygon([(0,0),(a,0),(a,b),(0,0)], color='blue', fill=False,axes=False)
t1=text("$1$",(a/2,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$",(a+.05,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{1}{2}$",(a/2,0-.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
s1=parametric_plot(.05*c(t), (t,0,alpha), color='red')
s2=parametric_plot(hyp+.05*c(t), (t,-pi/2-beta,-pi/2), color='red')
s3=line([(a-.05,0),(a-.05,.05),(a,.05)],color="red")
a1=text("$30^\circ$",.1*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
a2=text("$60^\circ$",hyp+.1*c(-pi/2-beta/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
# a3=text("$90^\circ$",leg+.1*c(3*pi/4),color="black",fontsize=16)
T+t1+t2+t3+s1+s2+s3+a1+a2
                    </sageplot>

                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let's start with the 45-45-90 triangle.
        Suppose a right triangle with a hypotenuse of length 1 has two angles of 45 degrees.
        Then the triangle is an isosceles triangle;
        that is, its two legs have the same length <m>a</m>,
        as shown in <xref ref="fig_TaalmanPage404c">Figure</xref>:
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig_TaalmanPage404c">
        <caption>A 45-45-90 triangle must have legs of the same length.</caption>
        <image width="28%" source="TaalmanPage404c.png"/>
      </figure>
      <p>
        By the Pythagorean Theorem,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}a^2+a^2 \amp = 1^2\\ 2a^2 \amp = 1\\ a^2 \amp = \frac{1}{2}\\ a \amp = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}}= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}}\right)= \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that we considered only the positive square root of
        <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> since we know that <m>a</m> is a length and thus must be positive.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now suppose that a right triangle has a hypotenuse of length 1, and angles of 30, 60, and 90 degrees.
        Let <m>a</m> be the length of the leg across from the 30-degree angle,
        and let <m>b</m> be the length of the leg across from the 60-degree angle.
        Two of these triangles together make the equilateral triangle in <xref ref="fig_TaalmanPage404d">Figure</xref> below:
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig_TaalmanPage404d">
        <caption>A 30-60-90 triangle can be doubled to form an equilateral triangle, with all three sides the same length as the hypotenuse.</caption>
        <image width="32%" source="TaalmanPage404d.png"/>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Since this triangle is equilateral, it follows that
        <me>
          2a = 1\qquad \Longleftrightarrow\qquad a = \frac{1}{2}
        </me>.
        By the Pythagorean Theorem,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}a^2+b^2 \amp = 1^2\\ \frac{1}{4}+b^2 \amp = 1\\ b^2 \amp =\frac{3}{4}\\ b \amp = \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Note that we considered only the positive square root in this calculation since <m>b</m> is a length and must be positive.
      </p>
    </proof>
    <p>
     We now endeavor to use <xref ref="th_special_triangles"/> to compute values of <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> for <m>\theta=\pi/3, \pi/4, \pi/6</m> radians (equivalently, <m>\theta=30, 45, 60</m> degrees). The method will be to add an appropriate right triangle to the unit circle picture described in Step 1 of <xref ref="proc_compute_sin_cos"/>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Let's see how this works with <m>\theta=\pi/4</m>, which has unit circle picture
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Unit circle picture for pi over 4</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi/4
beta=pi/4
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,pi/2+pi/30),color='blue',ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
Rad=line([(1,0),(0,0),hyp],color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.1*c(t),(t,0,alpha), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.1*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{4}$",.15*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2
        </sageplot>
    </image>
    <p>
        We now add a helpful right triangle to our unit circle, called a <term>reference triangle</term>, by dropping a perpendicular from <m>P=(x,y)</m> to the <m>x</m>-axis.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Unit circle picture for pi over 4 with reference triangle</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi/4
beta=pi/4
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,pi/2+pi/30),color='blue',ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
Rad=line([(1,0),(0,0),hyp],color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.1*c(t),(t,0,alpha), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.1*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{4}$",.15*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
tri=line([(0,0),hyp,(a,0),(0,0)], color='red')
l1=text(r"$\vert x\vert$",(a/2,+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
l2=text(r"$\vert y\vert$",(a+.05,b/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
l3=text(r"$1$",(a/2,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2+tri+l1+l2+l3
        </sageplot>
    </image>
        <p>
        The reference triangle will now allow us to determine the coordinates of the point <m>P</m>. Let's see why.  Note that the hypotenuse here has length 1, as it is a radius of the unit circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>. The two legs of the right triangle, on the other hand, have length equal to the <em>magnitudes</em> of the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-coordinates of the point <m>P=(x,y)</m>: that is, <m>\abs{x}</m> and <m>\abs{y}</m>, respectively. In this case, since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are both positive, we happen to have <m>\abs{x}=x</m> and <m>\abs{y}=y</m>. Since the angle at the origin is <m>\pi/4=45^\circ</m>, it follows that we are working with a 45-45-90 triangle. We conclude that 
        <md>
            <mrow>\cos\pi/4 \amp = x \amp (<xref ref="d_sine_cosine" text="global"/>)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \abs{x} \amp (x\geq 0\implies \abs{x}=x)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp (<xref ref="th_special_triangles" text="global"/>)</mrow>
            <mrow>\sin\pi/4 \amp = y \amp (<xref ref="d_sine_cosine" text="global"/>)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \abs{y} \amp (y\geq 0\implies \abs{y}=y)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp (<xref ref="th_special_triangles" text="global"/>)</mrow>
        </md>.
    The same technique can be used for any angle that appears in one of our two special triangles. The angle <m>\pi/6=30^\circ</m>, for example, has unit circle picture as depicted below, where we have added a useful right triangle.
    </p>
        <image xml:id="sageplot_30degrees" width="50%">
            <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of pi/6 with reference triangle</shortdescription>
<sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi/6
beta=pi/3
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,pi/2+pi/30),color='blue',ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
Rad=line([(1,0),(0,0),hyp],color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.1*c(t),(t,0,alpha), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.1*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{6}$",.15*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
tri=line([(0,0),hyp,(a,0),(0,0)], color='red')
l1=text(r"$\vert x\vert$",(a/2,+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
l2=text(r"$\vert y\vert$",(a+.05,b/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
l3=text(r"$1$",(a/2,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2+tri+l1+l2+l3      
</sageplot>
        </image>
    <p>
    Since the angle of the right triangle at the origin is <m>\pi/6=30^\circ</m>, the angle at <m>P</m> is <m>\pi/3=60^\circ</m>. Using our knowledge of 30-60-90 triangles, we conclude 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cos\pi/6 \amp = x \amp \sin\pi/6 \amp = y</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \abs{x} \amp \amp= \abs{y}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\amp \amp = \frac{1}{2}</mrow>
    </md>.
    Let's do the same thing with <m>\pi/3=60^\circ</m>.
</p>
         <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of pi/3 with reference triangle</shortdescription>
            <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi/3
beta=pi/6
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,pi/2+pi/30),color='blue',ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
Rad=line([(1,0),(0,0),hyp],color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.1*c(t),(t,0,alpha), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.1*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{3}$",.15*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
tri=line([(0,0),hyp,(a,0),(0,0)], color='red')
l1=text(r"$\vert x\vert$",(a/2,+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
l2=text(r"$\vert y\vert$",(a+.05,b/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
l3=text(r"$1$",(a/2,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2+tri+l1+l2+l3      
            </sageplot>
        </image>
    <p>
    Now the 60-degree angle (<m>\pi/3</m>) is at the origin and the 30-degree angle (<m>\pi/6</m>)is at <m>P</m>. We conclude 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cos\pi/3 \amp =x \amp \sin\pi/3 \amp = y</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \abs{x} \amp \amp= \abs{y}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\amp \amp = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
    </md>.
    In the three examples above, since the point <m>P=(x,y)</m> resided in the first quadrant of the plane, both its coordinates were positive, and as a result the values of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> were also positive. When the angle <m>\theta</m> is such that <m>P</m> lies in any other coordinate, we need to take account of the sign the coordinates of <m>P</m>. Consider <m>\theta=5\pi/6=150^\circ</m>. The unit circle with right triangle picture of this angle is shown below. 
</p>
      <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of 5\pi/6 with reference triangle</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=2*pi/3
beta=pi/3
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,pi+pi/30),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
Rad=line([(1,0),(0,0),hyp],color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.1*c(t),(t,0,alpha), color='red')
arc2=parametric_plot(.1*c(t),(t,pi-beta,pi), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.1*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{2\pi}{3}$",.15*c(alpha/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{3}$",.125*c(pi-beta/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
tri=line([(0,0),hyp,(a,0),(0,0)], color='red')
l1=text(r"$\vert x\vert$",(a/2,+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
l2=text(r"$\vert y\vert$",(a+.05,b/2),color="black",fontsize=16)
l3=text(r"$1$",(a/2,b/2+.05),color="black",fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2+t3+tri+l1+l2+l3    
        </sageplot>
      </image>
<p>
    The angle of our right triangle is <m>\pi/3=\pi-2\pi/3</m>, or <m>30</m> degrees, making the angle at <m>P</m> equal to 60 degrees. We thus have a 30-60-90 triangle, and conclude that 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cos 2\pi/3 \amp = x \amp \sin 2\pi/3\amp = y</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = -\abs{x} \amp \amp= \abs{y}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = -\frac{1}{2}\amp \amp = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
    </md>.
    This example makes clear the important difference between the <em>values</em> of the coordinates (<m>x</m> and <m>y</m>), and their <em>magnitudes</em> (<m>\abs{x}</m> and <m>\abs{y}</m>). We label the sides of the triangles with the magnitudes because these give the <em>lengths</em> of the sides. However, the outputs of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> are the actual coordinate values themselves, and not just their magnitudes. Since these values can be positive or negative as the point <m>P</m> makes its way around the unit circle, we need to take careful account of the signs when computing values of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m>. The diagram in <xref ref="fig_sign_coord_unit_circle"/> is a useful schema for this type of sign accounting. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig_sign_coord_unit_circle">
    <caption>Sign chart for coordinates of points in plane based on quadrant</caption>
<image width="75%">
    <shortdescription>Sign chart for coordinates of points in plane</shortdescription>
<sageplot>
f=plot(0,x,-1,1, ymin=-1, ymax=1, ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
t1=text("Quadrant I", (0.5, 0.75),color='black', fontsize=14)
t2=text("Quadrant II", (-0.5, 0.75),color='black', fontsize=14)
t3=text("Quadrant III", (-0.5, -0.75),color='black', fontsize=14)
t4=text("Quadrant IV", (0.5, -0.75),color='black', fontsize=14)
t5=text("$(+,+)$", (0.5, 0.5), color='black', fontsize=16)
t6=text("$(-,+)$", (-0.5, 0.5), color='black', fontsize=16)
t7=text("$(-,-)$", (-0.5, -0.5), color='black', fontsize=16)
t8=text("$(+,-)$", (0.5, -0.5), color='black', fontsize=16)
f+t1+t2+t3+t4+t5+t6+t7+t8
</sageplot>
</image>
</figure>
   
    <exercise xml:id="eg_coors_special_points">
      <statement>
        <p>
          In the diagram below we have specified the coordinates of the three points <m>P_\theta</m> on the unit circle corresponding to the angles <m>\theta=\pi/6, \pi/4, \pi/3</m>, as computed in the examples above.  
        </p>
        <p>
            Use symmetry to complete the diagram. In more detail, label each of the remaining points as <m>P_\theta</m>, where <m>\theta</m> indicates the radian measure of the central angle corresponding to the point, and provide explicit coordinates for each point.
        </p>
            <image width="75%">
                <shortdescription>Unit circle with coordinates of special points</shortdescription>
                <sageplot>
var('t')
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,0,2*pi),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
L=line([(0,0),c(pi/6)], linestyle='dashed', color='black')
p1=point([c(n*pi/6) for n in range(13)], size=50, color='red')
p2=point([c(n*pi/4) for n in range(9)], size=50, color='red')
t1=text(r"$P_{\pi/6}=(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\frac{1}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/6-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t2=text(r"$P_{\pi/4}=(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/4-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t3=text(r"$P_{\pi/3}=(\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/3-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
C+L+p1+p2+t1+t2+t3
                </sageplot>
            </image>
      </statement>
<solution>
    <p>
       Below you find the completed diagram.  
    </p>
    <image>
        <shortdescription>Completed unit circle diagram of special points</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
var('t')
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,0,2*pi),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
L=line([(0,0),c(pi/6)], linestyle='dashed', color='black')
p1=point([c(n*pi/6) for n in range(13)], size=50, color='red')
p2=point([c(n*pi/4) for n in range(9)], size=50, color='red')
t1=text(r"$P_{\pi/6}=(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\frac{1}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/6-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t2=text(r"$P_{\pi/4}=(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/4-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t3=text(r"$P_{\pi/3}=(\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/3-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t4=text(r"$P_{5\pi/6}=(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\frac{1}{2})$", 1.35*c(5*pi/6+.05), color='black', fontsize=14)
t5=text(r"$P_{3\pi/4}=(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.35*c(3*pi/4+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t6=text(r"$P_{2\pi/3}=(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.3*c(2*pi/3+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t7=text(r"$P_{7\pi/6}=(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},-\frac{1}{2})$", 1.4*c(7*pi/6-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t8=text(r"$P_{5\pi/4}=(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.4*c(5*pi/4-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t9=text(r"$P_{4\pi/3}=(-\frac{1}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.4*c(4*pi/3-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t10=text(r"$P_{11\pi/6}=(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},-\frac{1}{2})$", 1.4*c(11*pi/6+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t11=text(r"$P_{3\pi/2}=(0,-1)$", 1.2*c(3*pi/2+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t12=text(r"$P_{0}=(1,0)$", 1.35*c(2*pi+.04), color='black', fontsize=14)
t13=text(r"$P_{\pi}=(-1,0)$", 1.35*c(pi-.04), color='black', fontsize=14)
t14=text(r"$P_{\pi/2}=(0,1)$", 1.15*c(pi/2-.051), color='black', fontsize=14)
t15=text(r"$P_{5\pi/3}=(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.35*c(5*pi/3+.2), color='black', fontsize=14)
t16=text(r"$P_{7\pi/4}=(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.42*c(7*pi/4+.2), color='black', fontsize=14)
C+L+p1+p2+t1+t2+t3+t4+t5+t6+t7+t8+t9+t10+t11+t12+t13+t14+t15+t16
        </sageplot>
    </image>
</solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Computing with angles <m>\theta</m> outside of <m>[0,2\pi]</m></title>
    <p>
      You may have noticed that all of our examples of computations of <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> involved angles <m>\theta</m> between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m>. And yet, by definition of these functions, <m>\theta</m> is allowed to be <em>any</em> real number. How dow we compute these values values of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> for <m>\theta=35\pi/2</m>, or <m>\theta=-100\pi/3</m>? 
    </p>
    <p>
    Let's consider the example <m>\theta=16\pi/6</m>. Note that we have
    <md>
        <mrow>2\pi=\frac{12\pi}{6} \amp \leq \theta=\frac{16\pi}{6}\leq  4\pi=\frac{24\pi}{6}</mrow>
    </md>.
    Since <m>\theta</m> is between <m>2\pi</m> and <m>4\pi</m>, we visualize <m>\theta</m> as an angle that makes a one full rotation around the unit circle (<m>2\pi</m>) followed by some extra rotation between <m>0</m> and <m>2\pi</m>. Algebraically, we identify this extra rotation by expressing <m>\theta</m> as follows: 
    <md>
        <mrow>\theta \amp =\frac{16\pi}{6}=\frac{12\pi}{2}+\frac{4\pi}{6}=\underset{\text{full rot.}}{\underbrace{2\pi}}+\underset{\text{extra rot.}}{\underbrace{\frac{2\pi}{3}}}</mrow>
    </md>.
    It follows that the terminal edge of the angle <m>\theta=16\pi/6</m>, is the same as the terminal edge of the angle <m>2\pi/3</m>.  Graphically, we indicate the angle <m>\theta</m> as a counterclockwise spiralling arc ending at the terminal edge corresponding to <m>2\pi/3</m>. 
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig_unit_circle_bigangle">
        <caption>Unit circle picture of <m>16\pi/6</m></caption>
        <image width="75%">
            <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of 16 pi over 6</shortdescription>
            <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=16*pi/6
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,2*pi+pi/30),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
Rad=line([(0,0),hyp],color='blue')
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot((0.15*t+.075*(1-t))*c(alpha*t),(t,0,1), color='red')
arc2=parametric_plot(.3*c(2*pi/3*t),(t,0,1), color='green')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.15*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{16\pi}{6}$",.2*c(pi/6),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{2\pi}{3}$",.4*c(pi/3), color="black", fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2+arc2+t3
            </sageplot>
        </image>
    </figure>
<p>
    Since the angles <m>16\pi/6</m> and <m>2\pi/3</m> have the same terminal edge, the associated point <m>P=(x,y)</m> on the unit circle for each angle is the same. Thus we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cos 16\pi/6 \amp = x \amp \sin 16\pi/6 \amp=y </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =\cos 2\pi/3 \amp \amp=\sin 2\pi/3</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = -1/2 \amp \amp=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
    </md>.
    Two angles are called <term>coterminal</term> if they have the same terminal edge. The technique above can be summarized as follows: to compute <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> for an arbitrary angle <m>\theta</m>, find a <q>covenient</q> angle <m>\alpha</m> that is coterminal with <m>\theta</m>, in which case 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cos\theta \amp =\cos\alpha \amp \sin\theta\amp=\sin\alpha</mrow>
    </md>.
    A <q>convenient</q> angle usually means an angle <m>\alpha</m> (positive or negative) with <m>\abs{\alpha}\in [0,2\pi]</m>, since these angles are the most familiar to us. The algebraic trick to finding such a convenient coterminal angle is to locate the arbitrary angle <m>\theta</m> between two consecutive multiples of <m>2\pi</m>, and choose <m>\alpha</m> to be the difference between <m>\theta</m> and either one of these multiples. 
</p>
<p>
    Let's try this with a large negative angle. Consider <m>\theta=-11\pi/2</m>. Identifying the nearest multiples of <m>2\pi</m> to the left and right of <m>-11\pi/2</m>, we see that  
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>-4\pi=-8\pi/2 \amp \leq -11\pi/2 \leq -12\pi/2=-6\pi</mrow>
    </md>,
    and thus 
    <md>
        <mrow>-11\pi/2 \amp = -4\pi -3\pi/2</mrow>
    </md>.
    The last equation tells us that the angle <m>\theta=-11\pi/2</m> is the result of taking 2 full <em>clockwise</em> rotations around the circle (the <m>-4\pi</m> term), followed by an extra <em>clockwise</em> rotation of <m>3\pi/2</m> (the <m>-3\pi/2</m> term). As illustrated below, the angle of <m>-3\pi/2</m> is coterminal in turn to the angle <m>\pi/2</m>. 
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig_unit_circle_bigneg">
    <caption>Unit circle picture of <m>-11\pi/2</m></caption>
    <image width="75%">
        <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of -11 pi over 2</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=-11*pi/2
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,2*pi+pi/30),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
Rad=line([(0,0),hyp],color='blue', thickness=2)
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot((0.25*t+.075*(1-t))*c(alpha*t),(t,0,1), color='red')
arc2=parametric_plot(.375*c(pi/2*t),(t,0,1), color='green')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.15*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{-11\pi}{2}$",.3*c(-3*pi/4),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{2}$",.45*c(pi/3), color="black", fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t2+arc2+t3
        </sageplot>
    </image>
</figure>
<p>
    Since <m>-11\pi/2</m> is coterminal with <m>\pi/2</m>, we conclude that 
    <md>
        <mrow>\cos(-11\pi/2) \amp = \cos (\pi/2) \amp \sin(-11\pi/2)\amp=\sin(\pi/2)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = 0 \amp \amp= 1</mrow>
    </md>.
Let's make this technique of computing <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> values by hand official. 
</p>
<algorithm xml:id="proc_cos_sin_compute">
    <title>Computing trigonometric values by hand</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
           Let <m>\theta\in \R</m>. To compute <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> by hand, proceed as follows. 
           <ol>
            <li>
                <title>Find convenient coterminal angle</title>
                <p>
                    Find an angle <m>\alpha</m> with <m>\abs{\alpha}\in [0,2\pi]</m> such that <m>\theta=2\pi n +\alpha</m> for some <m>n</m>. The angles <m>\theta</m> and <m>\alpha</m> are coterminal.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Unit circle picture with reference triangle</title>
                
                
                <p>
                    Make a unit circle picture of the coterminal angles <m>\theta</m> and <m>\alpha</m> that inludes the point <m>P</m> where the terminal edge intersects the unit circle.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Add a reference triangle to the picture to determine the magnitudes <m>\abs{x}</m> and <m>\abs{y}</m> of the coordinates of <m>P</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Account for sign</title>
                <p>
                    Use the quadrant position of <m>P</m> to determine <m>x=\pm \abs{x}</m> and <m>y=\pm \abs{y}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Compute values</title>
                <p>
                    Conclude that 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\cos\theta \amp = x \amp \sin\theta\amp =y </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
           </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</algorithm>
<example xml:id="eg_compute_cos_sin">
<title>Computing <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Compute <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> for the given <m>\theta</m> using <xref ref="proc_compute_sin_cos"/>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\theta=-11\pi</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\theta=203\pi/4</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
          <m>\theta=-17\pi/6</m>  
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
See <xref ref="fig_comp_sin_cos"/> for the unit circle pictures for each of the angles <m>\theta</m>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            We have 
            <md>
                <mrow>-11\pi \amp = -5(2\pi)-\pi</mrow>
                <mrow> -11\pi\amp =-6(2\pi)+\pi </mrow>
            </md>.
            These equations tell us that <m>\theta</m> is coterminal to <m>-\pi</m> and <m>\pi</m>. We can use either one of these angles to compue compute <m>\cos\theta</m>. We choose <m>\pi</m>: 
            <md>
                <mrow>\cos \theta \amp =\cos \pi=-1 \amp \sin\theta\amp =\sin \pi=0</mrow>
            </md> .
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            We have 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>203\pi/4 \amp =200\pi/4+3\pi/4</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 25(2\pi)+3\pi/4</mrow>
            </md>.
            Thus <m>\theta</m> is coterminal to <m>3\pi/4</m>. We conclude that 
            <md>
                <mrow>\cos\theta \amp =\cos 3\pi/4 \amp \sin\theta\amp =\sin 3\pi/4</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = -\sqrt{2}/2 \amp \amp =\sqrt{2}/2</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            We have 
            <md>
                <mrow>-17\pi/6 \amp = -12\pi/6 -5\pi/6</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \amp = -2(2\pi)-5\pi/6</mrow>
            </md>.
            Thus <m>\theta</m> is coterminal to <m>-5\pi/6</m>. We conclude that 
            <md>
                <mrow>\cos\theta \amp = \cos -5\pi/6 \amp \sin\theta \amp = \sin -5\pi/6</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = -\sqrt{3}/2 \amp \amp = -1/2</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
</example>
<figure xml:id="fig_comp_sin_cos">
    <caption>Unit circle pictures for coterminal angles <m>\theta</m> and <m>\alpha</m></caption>
    <sbsgroup>
    <sidebyside widths="52% 45%" valign="middle">
        
    <figure xml:id="fig_pimult">
        <caption><m>\theta=-11\pi</m>, <m>\alpha=\pi</m></caption>
        <image width="75%">
            <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of -11 pi and pi</shortdescription>
            <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=pi
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,2*pi+pi/30),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
Rad=line([(0,0),hyp],color='blue', thickness=2)
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.2*c(alpha*t),(t,0,1), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.25*c(alpha-.1),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\pi$",.3*c(pi/2), color="black", fontsize=16)
C+P+Rad+arc+t1+t3
            </sageplot>
        </image>
    </figure>    
    <figure xml:id="fig_big_pi_over_4">
        <caption><m>\theta=203\pi/4</m>, <m>\alpha=3\pi/4</m></caption>
        <image>
            <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of 203 pi over 4 and 3 pi over 4</shortdescription>
            <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=3*pi/4
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,2*pi+pi/30),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
L=line([(0,0),hyp,leg,(0,0)],color='red')
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.2*c(alpha*t),(t,0,1), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.15*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{4}$",.3*c(pi-pi/8),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{3\pi}{4}$",.3*c(alpha/2), color="black", fontsize=16)
C+P+L+arc+t1+t2+t3
            </sageplot>
        </image>
    </figure>
</sidebyside>
            
    <sidebyside width="50%">
    <figure xml:id="fig_big_pi_six">
        <caption><m>\theta=-17\pi/6</m>, <m>\alpha=-5\pi/6</m></caption>
        <image>
            <shortdescription>Unit circle picture of -17 pi over 6 and -5 pi over 6</shortdescription>
            <sageplot>
var('t')
alpha=-5*pi/6
a=cos(alpha)
b=sin(alpha)
hyp=vector([a,b])
leg=vector([a,0])
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,-pi/30,2*pi+pi/30),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
L=line([(0,0),hyp,leg,(0,0)],color='red')
P=point(c(alpha), size=50, color='blue')
arc=parametric_plot(.2*c(alpha*t),(t,0,1), color='red')
t1=text("$P=(x,y)$",1.15*c(alpha),color="black",fontsize=16)
t2=text(r"$\frac{\pi}{6}$",.3*c(pi+pi/12),color="black",fontsize=16)
t3=text(r"$\frac{-5\pi}{6}$",.3*c(alpha/2.5), color="black", fontsize=16)
C+P+L+arc+t1+t2+t3
            </sageplot>
        </image>
    </figure>
   </sidebyside>
    </sbsgroup>
</figure>
<remark>
    <title>Computing values of <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> by hand</title>
    <p>
        In order to complete <m>\cos</m> and <m>\sin</m> computation using <xref ref="proc_compute_sin_cos"/>, we need the reference triangles introduced to have side lengths that we can compute by hand. This means that, for the moment we are only able to compute <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> by hand for angles <m>\theta</m> that are coterminal with one of the sixteen angles included in <xref ref="fig_unit_circle_familiar"/>. We will refer to these angles as the <term>familiar angles</term>. If in Step 1 of <xref ref="proc_compute_sin_cos"/> we find that <m>\theta</m> is coterminal to an angle <m>\alpha</m> that is <em>not</em> one of these familiar angles, then (at the moment) we are not able to compute <m>\cos\theta</m> and <m>\sin\theta</m> by hand.
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, the angle <m>\theta=1</m> (measured in radians) lies within the interval <m>[0,2\pi]</m>. But clearly <m>1</m> is not equal to any of the familiar angles in <xref ref="fig_unit_circle_familiar"/>, and thus we are not able to give a simple explicit expression for <m>\cos 1</m> and <m>\sin 1</m> by hand. Of course, it is possible use technology to <em>estimate</em> such values with a decimal approximation: <eg/>, 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow>\cos 1 \amp \approx 0.54 \amp \sin 1\amp \approx 0.84</mrow>
        </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Even without a calculator in hand, from the approximation <m>\pi\approx 3.14</m>, we see that
        <md>
            <mrow> \pi/4 \amp \leq 1\leq \pi/3 </mrow>
        </md>.
        This means that if we were to add the point <m>P_1</m> for <m>\theta=1</m> to the unit circle picture in <xref ref="fig_unit_circle_familiar"/>, it would be located between <m>P_{\pi/4}</m> and <m>P_{\pi/3}</m>. But then, for example, the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_1</m> would be greater than the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_{\pi/3}</m> and less than the <m>x</m>-coordinate of <m>P_{\pi/4}</m>. Since the value of <m>\cos</m> at these angles is equal to this <m>x</m>-coordinate, we conclude that 
        <md>
            <mrow>\cos \pi/3 \amp \leq \cos 1\leq \cos \pi/4</mrow>
        </md>
        or equivalently, 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow>\frac{1}{2} \amp \leq \cos 1 \leq \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</mrow>
        </md>.
        Indeed, the first inequality above <m>0.5\leq \cos 1</m> is born out by our approximation <m>\cos 1\approx 0.54</m>. 
    </p>
    
</remark>
<figure xml:id="fig_unit_circle_familiar">
    <caption>The 16 familiar angles of the unit circle</caption>
    <image width="100%">
        <shortdescription>Unit circle with 16 familiar angles</shortdescription>
        <sageplot>
var('t')
c(t)=vector([cos(t),sin(t)])
C=parametric_plot(c(t),(t,0,2*pi),color='blue', ticks=[[-1,-.5,.5,1],[-1,-.5,.5,1]])
L=line([(0,0),c(pi/6)], linestyle='dashed', color='black')
p1=point([c(n*pi/6) for n in range(13)], size=50, color='red')
p2=point([c(n*pi/4) for n in range(9)], size=50, color='red')
t1=text(r"$P_{\pi/6}=(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\frac{1}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/6-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t2=text(r"$P_{\pi/4}=(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/4-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t3=text(r"$P_{\pi/3}=(\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.3*c(pi/3-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t4=text(r"$P_{5\pi/6}=(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},\frac{1}{2})$", 1.35*c(5*pi/6+.05), color='black', fontsize=14)
t5=text(r"$P_{3\pi/4}=(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.35*c(3*pi/4+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t6=text(r"$P_{2\pi/3}=(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.3*c(2*pi/3+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t7=text(r"$P_{7\pi/6}=(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},-\frac{1}{2})$", 1.4*c(7*pi/6-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t8=text(r"$P_{5\pi/4}=(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.4*c(5*pi/4-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t9=text(r"$P_{4\pi/3}=(-\frac{1}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.4*c(4*pi/3-.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t10=text(r"$P_{11\pi/6}=(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},-\frac{1}{2})$", 1.4*c(11*pi/6+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t11=text(r"$P_{3\pi/2}=(0,-1)$", 1.2*c(3*pi/2+.1), color='black', fontsize=14)
t12=text(r"$P_{0}=(1,0)$", 1.35*c(2*pi+.04), color='black', fontsize=14)
t13=text(r"$P_{\pi}=(-1,0)$", 1.35*c(pi-.04), color='black', fontsize=14)
t14=text(r"$P_{\pi/2}=(0,1)$", 1.15*c(pi/2-.051), color='black', fontsize=14)
t15=text(r"$P_{5\pi/3}=(-\frac{1}{2},\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2})$", 1.35*c(5*pi/3+.2), color='black', fontsize=14)
t16=text(r"$P_{7\pi/4}=(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})$", 1.42*c(7*pi/4+.2), color='black', fontsize=14)
C+L+p1+p2+t1+t2+t3+t4+t5+t6+t7+t8+t9+t10+t11+t12+t13+t14+t15+t16
        </sageplot>
    </image>
</figure>
  </subsection>
 
 
</section>